    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-05-22T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-05-22T00:00:00-05:00" n="283"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d283">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 EW 1939/2635</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Chief of the Division of Central European
                        Affairs</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Riddleberger</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to Mr. <persName type="to">Fletcher
                            Warren</persName>, Executive Assistant to the Assistant Secretary of
                        State</hi> (<persName>
                        <hi rend="italic">Berle</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-05-22">May 22,
                            1944</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Mr. Warren</hi>: I return herewith the O.S.S. report<note
                        n="9" xml:id="d283fn9">Dated May 16, <ref target="#pg_510">p.
                        510</ref>.</note> on the most recent German peace feeler in Switzerland.
                    Under arrangements made at Moscow,<note n="10" xml:id="d283fn10">For
                        correspondence on the Tripartite Conference of Foreign Ministers, October
                        18–November 1, 1943, see <ref target="frus1943v01#pg_513">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1943, vol. 1, pp. 513</ref>
                        ff.</note> the three powers are supposed to inform one another of any peace
                    feelers which they may receive. I have consequently drafted communications to
                    the British and Soviet Embassies advising them of this matter.<note n="11"
                        xml:id="d283fn11">See footnote 90, <ref target="#pg_510">p.
                        510</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Could you request O.S.S. to inform its representative in Switzerland of the
                    position of this government with respect to such peace feelers.<note n="12"
                        xml:id="d283fn12">Marginal note in text, presumably in reply to this
                        request, read as follows: “This will be done when file is returned to me
                        after <hi rend="italic">aide-m</hi>[<hi rend="italic">émoire</hi>]’s are
                        sent.” See footnote 90, <ref target="#pg_510">p. 510</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">James</hi> W. <hi rend="smallcaps">Riddleberger</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
